        <h1>AD Enumeration</h1>

        <h2>Why AD Enumeration Comes First</h2>
        <p>Active Directory is the identity and access backbone of nearly every enterprise Windows environment. Getting initial access is only the beginning — understanding the AD structure tells you who has what access, where the attack paths lead, and how to move from a low-privilege foothold to Domain Admin. Enumeration without context wastes access. Enumeration with context maps your path.</p>
        <p>The goal: identify <strong>users with special attributes</strong> (SPNs, no pre-auth, AdminCount=1), <strong>groups with elevated permissions</strong> (Domain Admins, Account Operators), <strong>computers with interesting delegations</strong>, and <strong>ACL edges</strong> that create unexpected privilege paths.</p>

        <div class="diagram-container">
          <img src="/images/active-directory/ad-enum-tree.svg" alt="Active Directory enumeration tree: LDAP queries reveal users, groups, computers, GPOs, trusts, and ACLs">
          <div class="diagram-label">// ad enumeration — object types and attack relevance</div>
        </div>

